{
  "text": "Measuring energy consumption, however, traditionally requires custom instrumentation of the hardware; a barrier that prevents energy consumption from being treated as a first class software design goal. As cryptographic implementations for software are often developed directly in assembly language and are relatively simple, power models that work on the ISA level would seem to be ideal for profiling, understanding and improving their energy consumption. One type of energy model that works on this level is a statistical model proposed by Tiwari et al. [CITATION_1] that uses measured information about the energy cost of different instruction sequences to derive a model for estimating and giving transparency to the energy consumption of any given piece of assembly code.",
  "citation_candidates": [
